# B2 Dashboard — Supabase connection settings.
#
# Copy these two values into .env when cutting over. Everything else in .env
# (WATI, Resend, CRON_SECRET, seeds…) is unchanged by the database move.
#
# Project: vyuzqkzujjbgccfjhjcr · ap-southeast-1 (Singapore) · Postgres 17.6
# Dashboard -> Connect -> copy the POOLER strings (see the IPv6 warning below).
#
# ─────────────────── Use the POOLER for both. Not db.<ref>.supabase.co ───────────────────
#
# The "direct" host `db.<ref>.supabase.co` is **IPv6-only** — Supabase dropped IPv4 on
# direct connections and now sells it as an add-on. On an IPv4-only network it fails with
#     could not translate host name "db.<ref>.supabase.co" to address
# which reads like DNS being broken. It is not: the name resolves, but to an AAAA record
# only. Confirmed on this machine — it has no IPv6 route at all.
#
# So BOTH URLs below use `aws-0-ap-southeast-1.pooler.supabase.com`, which is IPv4:
#
#   :6543  transaction pooler — the app.        Needs ?pgbouncer=true
#   :5432  SESSION pooler     — migrations.     The IPv4 stand-in for a direct connection
#
# Session mode hands you a dedicated backend for the whole session, so it carries the
# session-level statements DDL needs. `prisma migrate deploy` works over it (verified),
# and so does `SET session_replication_role` in the migration script.
#
# ─────────────────── Two gotchas that cost real time ───────────────────
#
# 1. USERNAME IS DIFFERENT ON THE POOLER: `postgres.<project_ref>`, not `postgres`.
#    Get it wrong and the pooler says `Tenant or user not found` — which sounds like a
#    dead project, but only means the username did not carry the ref.
#
# 2. PERCENT-ENCODE THE PASSWORD. `@` must be `%40`, and `#` -> `%23`, `/` -> `%2F`,
#    `:` -> `%3A`. `@` also separates credentials from host, so a raw one makes parsers
#    read the host as `<rest-of-password>@aws-0-…`. This surfaces as bogus
#    "password authentication failed" or "host not found" errors.

# ─────────────────── App runtime (transaction pooler, :6543) ───────────────────
# `connection_limit=1` is deliberate: each serverless invocation opens its own pool and
# the pooler has a hard client cap (this project is t4g.nano — 60 connections total).
# Raise it only on a single long-lived VM.
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres.vyuzqkzujjbgccfjhjcr:PASSWORD_URLENCODED@aws-0-ap-southeast-1.pooler.supabase.com:6543/postgres?pgbouncer=true&connection_limit=1"

# ─────────────────── Migrations + scripts (session pooler, :5432) ───────────────────
# Used by `prisma migrate deploy`, scripts/migrate-to-supabase.mjs, and `npm run db:lockdown`.
DIRECT_URL="postgresql://postgres.vyuzqkzujjbgccfjhjcr:PASSWORD_URLENCODED@aws-0-ap-southeast-1.pooler.supabase.com:5432/postgres"

# ─────────────────── NOT needed ───────────────────
#
# No SUPABASE_URL / SUPABASE_ANON_KEY / SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY.
# The app reaches Postgres over the wire protocol via Prisma; it never calls the Supabase
# REST API. scripts/supabase-lockdown.sql revoked anon + authenticated precisely so those
# keys read nothing — verified: `SET ROLE anon; SELECT count(*) FROM lead;` ->
# `permission denied for table lead`. If you ever add a key here, read that script first.
#
# NOTE: `service_role` is deliberately NOT revoked — it is BYPASSRLS by design and is the
# break-glass/admin identity. Its key is a SECRET: never put it in a browser bundle, a
# NEXT_PUBLIC_* var, or a client component. It bypasses every protection above.

# ─────────────────── After cutover ───────────────────
#
#  - BETTER_AUTH_URL must become the real public https origin. While it says localhost,
#    password-reset and agreement-signing links in email go nowhere.
#  - REDIS_URL: Supabase has no Redis. Leave it UNSET and the automation queue falls back
#    to Postgres polling (WorkflowEnrollment.nextRunAt) — the documented, supported path.
#  - Rotate the DB password and every secret that has lived in the local .env.
